gtr:otherNames>Clare</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Lindley</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE002110%2F1"><gtr:id>C8F754D8-3121-422F-8576-2D8B8F11B0CC</gtr:id><gtr:title>THE DYNAMICS AND POLITICS OF MIGRANT REMITTANCES TO WAR-TORN SOCIETIES</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E002110/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The research project?s aim is to develop previous analysis of migrants? remittances in war-torn societies. Remittances (money that migrants send home) have considerable effects in migrants? countries of origin and for this reason are the subject of increasing research and policy interest. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This project moves beyond the traditional focus on labour migration, showing how forced migration also creates opportunities for remitting and exploring the dynamics and effects of the remittance process in conflict-affected countries of origin and among diaspora groups. Focusing in particular on the Somali case, the project is based on further analysis of interview and survey data collected in 2004 and 2005 in the country of origin (in Hargeisa, a northern Somali city), in the wider region (in the Eastleigh district of Nairobi), and in a western host country (in London). The findings are relevant to contemporary debates on migration and development, conflict situations, and global refugee issues.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>65983</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>F5C9D70C-7EFA-48A3-91D8-4C8591814268</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Early-Morning Phonecall: Remittances from a Refugee Diaspora Perspective</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of Ethnic and Migration Studies</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/d4dfaf1dee0378ed92b021bb63a74ad9"><gtr:id>d4dfaf1dee0378ed92b021bb63a74ad9</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Lindley A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author><